> </span><br><span id=notbold>13 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Aug 19th 2:17 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.40]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Fear Kiting.<br><br>At level 15 a shadowknights ability to solo increases exponentially.&nbsp;&nbsp;The main factor for this, IMHO is the ability to fear kite.  I enjoy soloing and have been since the creation of my character (currently I am a 22nd level EruSK).  Fear kiting isn't really kiting at all in the classic sense of having a monster chase you and caster spells on it from afar.  Fear kiting is pretty close to the oposite.  What is involved with fear kiting is casting some kind of movement reducing spell (to allow you to keep up with the mob when it flees), in our case the Darkness line of spells, and then fearing the mob.  This tactic can be immensely effective and efficient.  Not only is the mob NOT hitting you but you are taking full swing at it from behind for the duration of your fear spell, or if the need arises you can drain without worring about interuptions.  Keep in mind fear kiting can really only be done effectively in the larger, flatter, outdoor areas of the game (Karrannas, Ros, even the commons, and many Kunark zones are good examples).  As well you wouldn't want to do it in an area where the might be mobs around that are aggro to you, or assist the mobs on witch you intend on fighting (Lions are good example mobs).  The reason, of course, is you don't want to send one mob running only to have 2 more return.  I find the best way to initiate combat is to, from the farthest distance allowed, cast my drain strength spell.  Then as the mob comes running I will back off until my spell gems refresh and cast darkness.  By this time the mob has normally arrived (if not a bit sooner, in witch case I still work on casting darkness).  I then back of just out of reach and let my pet take just enough hits to let me cast fear (they CAN actually take a FEW hits at this level).  One thing to always keep in mind is that fear is INCREDIBLY easy to interrupt.  Once the fear has landed its all a free for all slashing on the mobs backside.  As you fight make sure and keep an eye about for the darkness fading message, as you'll almost always wanna have darkness on if you plan on keeping up with the mob.  Once your fear has worn , depending on the amount of damage you did, you can sometimes back off and fear again.  If the mob sticks on you, you have a couple of options.  Either just slug it out, or try and fear again.  But as I said if the mobs is hitting you AT ALL you'll more than likely get interupted.  This is where darkness again can come into play.  Depending on the speed of the mob you can run away, putting enough ground between you and the mob, to again cast fear (fear takes a dam long time to cast, so you'll need quite a bit of ground).  Be warned some mobs with naturally high speeds arent slowed enough by darkness to allow this gaining of ground.  Well I think that about covers it.  As well I should note since we just gained our newly adjusted mana pools, we do this tactic quite a bit more per bar of mana than we used to.  I hope this helps out anyone who had any questions about this great tactic.  Feel free to add any corrections and any higher level adjustments that come with mobs above 23.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
